            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD had received a pamphlet by Oscar Schmidt, ‘War Goethe ein Darwinianer?’. See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8079.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from S. R. S. Norton, 20 November [1871]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1222.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Francis Darwin</ref> and <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1224.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">George Howard Darwin</ref> visited America between August and October 1871 (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7867.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Asa Gray, 16 July [1871]</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">Anne and <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5559.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Grace Ashburner</ref>. See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8079.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from S. R. S. Norton, 20 November [1871]</ref> and n. 6.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8079.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from S. R. S. Norton, 20 November [1871]</ref>. CD refers to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1240.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Sara Sedgwick</ref> and <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_6724.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Arthur George Sedgwick</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_6447.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Catherine Eliot Norton</ref> was Susan Norton’s mother-in-law.</note>
